Here is an example of how you can solve this problem in Julia:

```julia
function extract_julia_code(md::String)
    # Find all code blocks
    blocks = matchall(r"```julia\n(.*?)\n```", md, captures=true);

    # Remove code fences and join the code blocks together with a newline
    code = join([block[1] for block in blocks], "\n");

    return code;
end
```

This function uses regular expressions to find all code blocks in the markdown document. It then removes the code fences from each block and joins them into one string with newline characters between each block of code.

Please note that this is a very simple implementation and might not work perfectly for more complex cases, such as code blocks containing backticks or newlines. For a more robust solution, you would need to use a proper markdown parsing library.
